The combustion of fossil fuels from human activities is largely responsible for the increase in carbon dioxide (CO2) concentrations in the atmosphere together with the resulting increase in global temperature and climate change. The increasing demand for energy results in the accumulation of CO2, the most important greenhouse gas, because of the way energy is produced. Most countries rely on fossil fuels (oil, gas and coal) to satisfy their energy demand. These fuels need to be burned so that the heat released in the process can be converted to energy. The carbon in the fuel reacts with oxygen, producing CO2 that is released to the atmosphere. Air pollutants (sulphur dioxide, nitrogen oxides and particulates) are also released, with resulting impacts on air quality. However, due to technical measures and improvements in power and heat generation plants, emissions of air pollutants have been declining over the past decades.
The economy continues to grow as does energy consumption. Fossil fuels still dominate the fuel mix — about 79&nbsp;% of the energy needs of the average European are met by coal, gas and oil. Around 13&nbsp;% comes from nuclear power and the remaining 8&nbsp;% comes from rapidly increasing renewable energy sources (especially wind and solar energy). The average European uses the equivalent of 3.7&nbsp;tonnes of oil per year on electricity, heating and transport. This corresponds to 7.8&nbsp;tonnes of energy-related CO2 emissions. This varies widely between countries, depending partly on the uptake of renewable energy sources. Transport has been the fastest-growing energy-using sector since 1990 and is now the largest consumer of energy.

